\title{diamondback: Fast Patch-Based Analysis of Very Large Categorical Rasters}
\description{
Connected-component labelling, patch metrics, core-area calculation and temporal patch lineage analysis for categorical and binary rasters with hundreds of millions of cells. Raster input/output, geometry and validation stay in R via 'terra'; the array kernels are delegated to NumPy and SciPy through 'reticulate', which is typically far faster than pure-R connected-component labelling on large grids. Includes explicit handling of missing values and study-area masks, memory estimation before allocation, result caching keyed on input fingerprints, and validation of results against independent checks.
}
\section{Getting started}{

Check the environment once, then analyse:

\if{html}{\out{<div class="sourceCode r">}}\preformatted{diamondback_check()

library(terra)
forest <- rast("forest_1985.tif")
study  <- rast("study_area.tif")

p1985 <- analyze_patches(forest, class = 1, mask = study, output_dir = "derived/1985")
p2024 <- analyze_patches(rast("forest_2024.tif"), class = 1, mask = study,
                         output_dir = "derived/2024")

change <- compare_patches(p1985, p2024)
}\if{html}{\out{</div>}}
}

