\section{How NA is treated}{

diamondback keeps four cell states apart --- patch, valid background, outside
the analysis domain, and missing --- and \code{NA} is never silently folded into
any of them. See \code{\link[=label_patches]{label_patches()}} for the full account. This is the single
most important thing to understand before trusting the numbers.
}

\section{Python}{

The array kernels run in NumPy and SciPy via reticulate. Nothing is installed
when the package loads; the backend is resolved the first time a computation
needs it, using \code{reticulate::py_require()}. Run \code{\link[=diamondback_check]{diamondback_check()}} if
anything looks wrong.
}

\section{Limitations in this version}{

Labelling holds the array in RAM, which is what \code{scipy.ndimage.label()}
requires. \code{\link[=db_memory_report]{db_memory_report()}} estimates the cost of a raster before you
commit to it, and every entry point errors before allocating rather than
after. \code{\link[=patch_core_area]{patch_core_area()}} needs a projected raster; everything else supports
lon/lat exactly.
}

